snational, and imperial phenomenon. White supremacy is sustained through the construction of inferiority and anti-Blackness. The context, history, and perspective offered by Collins, Newman, and Jun should serve as an introduction to the disruption of the ways in which university and academic dispositions have and continue to serve as sites of colonial and White supremacist preservation—as well as sites of resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducation, Colonial. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspects. 0aRacism against Black people. 0aRacism in higher education. 0aWhite nationalism. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  arace, diaspora, colonization, conquest, migration, immigration, black, white, african, european, culture, anti-blackness, racism, univeirsty academia, Brazil, Asitralia, New Zealand, indigenous, indigenous people, South Africa, Cape Town, Sydney, academia, global south, brown, eurocentric, global.1 aJun, Alexander, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNewman, Christopher B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197883188940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978831889423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978831889/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK